9 FEB 26 :

    PHYSICAL SERVER
    --------------------------------------------------
        • A real hardware machine.
        • CPU, RAM, Storage installed directly.
        • Runs one operating system.
        • Limited scalability and very expensive to maintain.


    VMWARE (VIRTUALIZATION)
    --------------------------------------------------
          Provides virtualization software.
        • Multiple virtual machines run on one physical server.
        • Each VM has its own OS and apps.
        • Better resource usage than physical servers.
        • Still managed by you (on-premise).


    CLOUD
    --------------------------------------------------
        • Computers (servers) available over the internet.
        • You don’t manage hardware; cloud provider manages it.
        • Pay only for what you use.
        • Scalable, reliable, global.


    PUBLIC CLOUD
    --------------------------------------------------
        • Cloud owned by a provider (AWS, Azure, GCP).
        • You rent servers from them.
        • Shared infrastructure with isolation.
        • Most common and cost-effective.


    PRIVATE CLOUD
    --------------------------------------------------
        • Cloud infrastructure dedicated to ONE organization.
        • Hosted in your data center or fully isolated environment.
        • More control, more security, more cost.


    VIRTUAL PRIVATE CLOUD (VPC)
    --------------------------------------------------
        • A private network inside the public cloud.
        • Your own isolated section of AWS/Azure/GCP.
        • You control:
              - IP ranges
              - Subnets
              - Routing
              - Security groups
              - Firewalls
        • Like having your own private data center inside the cloud.


    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------
        Physical Server     → One big hardware machine  
        VMware Virtualization → Many VMs on one physical server  
        Cloud               → Servers delivered over the internet  
        Public Cloud        → Shared platform for everyone  
        Private Cloud       → Cloud dedicated to one company  
        VPC                 → Your private network inside public cloud  
		
		
------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A VPC?

    --------------------------------------------------
    VPC = Virtual Private Cloud
    --------------------------------------------------

        • A VPC is your own private network inside 
          Amazon Web Services (AWS).
        • You fully control:
              - IP ranges
              - Subnets
              - Routing
              - Firewalls (SG + NACL)
        • Think of it as your own data center inside AWS.


    WHAT ARE SUBNETS?

    --------------------------------------------------
        • Subnets are smaller network segments inside a VPC.
        • Two main types:
              - Public Subnet  → Has internet access
              - Private Subnet → No direct internet access
        • You usually create:
              - Public subnet (for ALB, Bastion/jump server )
              - Private subnet (for EC2, DB)


    WHAT IS AN INTERNET GATEWAY (IGW)?

    --------------------------------------------------
        • IGW allows your VPC to connect to the internet.
        • Without an IGW, nothing inside the VPC
          can access the internet.
        • Only public subnets can use IGW.


    WHAT IS A ROUTE TABLE?

    --------------------------------------------------
        • A route table decides where network traffic should go.
        • Each subnet must be associated with a route table.

        Example routes:
            10.0.0.0/16 → local    (VPC internal traffic)
            0.0.0.0/0   → igw-id   (internet traffic via IGW)

        Public Subnet Route Table:
            Has 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW

        Private Subnet Route Table:
            No IGW route  
            May have route to NAT Gateway for outgoing traffic


    HOW WE CONFIGURE A VPC (SIMPLE STEPS)

    --------------------------------------------------
        1. Create VPC
              Example: CIDR = 10.81.0.0/16

        2. Create Subnets
              - 10.81.1.0/24 (public)
              - 10.81.2.0/24 (private)
              - Spread across multiple AZs

        3. Create Internet Gateway (IGW)
              - Attach it to the VPC

        4. Create Route Tables
              - Public RT: Add 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW
              - Private RT: No internet route

        5. Associate Subnets with Route Tables
              - Public subnets → Public RT
              - Private subnets → Private RT

        Optional:
        6. Add NAT Gateway (for private subnet outbound internet)
        7. Add Security Groups & NACLs
        8. Launch EC2 instances in correct subnets


    SIMPLE SUMMARY

    --------------------------------------------------
        VPC        → Your private network in AWS  
        Subnet     → Smaller network inside VPC  
        IGW        → Allows internet access  
        Route Table→ Controls where traffic goes  
        Setup      → Create VPC → Subnets → IGW → Routes → Associate  
		



