    PUBLIC IP VS PRIVATE IP IN AWS (SHORT NOTES)

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A PRIVATE IP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Assigned to an EC2 instance inside a VPC.
        • Used for internal communication only.
        • Cannot be accessed from the internet.
        • Always stays within the AWS network.

        Example:
            10.0.1.25
            172.31.22.10

        Private IP is permanent for the instance (unless changed).


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A PUBLIC IP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Assigned to an EC2 in a PUBLIC subnet.
        • Allows access from the internet.
        • Changes when the instance stops/starts 
          (unless it's an Elastic IP).

        Example:
            3.110.45.120


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY DOES AWS USE BOTH PUBLIC AND PRIVATE IPs?
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Security  
            - Private IP keeps internal servers hidden.
            - Only selected servers get public IPs.

        2) Cost-saving  
            - Internet traffic via public IP costs more.
            - Internal private IP traffic is cheaper.

        3) Isolation  
            - Databases and backend apps must stay private.
            - Frontend/ALB need public access.

        4) Flexibility  
            - Public for internet-facing systems  
            - Private for internal microservices  


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY TWO IPs? 
    --------------------------------------------------

        Because:
            • Private IP → For internal communication  
            • Public IP  → For internet communication  

        Example:
            - Front-end EC2 needs public IP to serve users.
            - Back-end EC2 and DB only need private IP (no internet).


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW AWS DECIDES WHICH IP TO ASSIGN?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • If EC2 is in a PUBLIC subnet + Auto-assign Public IP = enabled  
              → It gets both Public + Private

        • If EC2 is in a PRIVATE subnet  
              → It gets ONLY a Private IP


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Private IP = Internal-only, safe, inside VPC  
        Public IP  = Internet-facing, accessible globally  

        AWS uses both for:
            - Security
            - Isolation
            - Cost control
            - Architecture best practices


--------------------------------------------------------------------------

    WHAT IS A SECURITY GROUP IN AWS?

        A Security Group (SG) in
        Amazon Web Services (AWS)
        is a virtual firewall that controls
        **which traffic is allowed IN and OUT**
        of your EC2 instances or services.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY DO WE NEED SECURITY GROUPS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Protect servers from unwanted traffic  
        • Allow only permitted ports (SSH, HTTP, HTTPS)  
        • Block all other traffic by default  
        • Increase security inside the VPC  
        • Control access at the instance level  


    --------------------------------------------------
    IMPORTANT FEATURES
    --------------------------------------------------

        • SGs are stateful  
              - If inbound is allowed, outbound response is auto-allowed

        • Deny is implicit  
              - If a rule is not allowed, it is automatically blocked

        • Can attach multiple SGs to one EC2  
        • Can reuse the same SG for multiple EC2s  


    --------------------------------------------------
    INBOUND RULES
    --------------------------------------------------

        Defines what traffic can ENTER the instance.

        Example:
            Port 22  → Allow SSH
            Port 80  → Allow HTTP
            Port 443 → Allow HTTPS


    --------------------------------------------------
    OUTBOUND RULES
    --------------------------------------------------

        Defines what traffic can LEAVE the instance.

        Default:
            All outbound traffic is allowed.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHERE SECURITY GROUPS ARE USED?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • EC2 instances  
        • Load Balancers  
        • RDS databases  
        • Lambda functions (inside VPC)  
        • ENIs (Elastic Network Interfaces)  


    --------------------------------------------------
    SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Security Group = Instance-level firewall  
        Controls: who can talk to your server  
        Default: everything blocked except what you allow  
        Works at: inbound + outbound, stateful behavior  


******************************************************************************************************

    WHAT IS A NACL IN AWS?

    --------------------------------------------------
    DEFINITION
    --------------------------------------------------

        A NACL (Network Access Control List) in
        Amazon Web Services (AWS)
        is a firewall that controls traffic
        **at the subnet level**, not instance level.

        It filters traffic entering or leaving a subnet.


    --------------------------------------------------
    KEY FEATURES OF NACL
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Works at subnet level  
        • Stateless (does NOT remember previous traffic)  
        • You must explicitly allow both inbound and outbound  
        • Has numbered rules (evaluated in order)  
        • Can allow or deny traffic  


    --------------------------------------------------
    DEFAULT NACL BEHAVIOR
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Default NACL → allows everything  
        • Custom NACL → denies everything until you add rules  


    --------------------------------------------------
    NACL VS SECURITY GROUP (SHORT NOTES)
    --------------------------------------------------

        Security Group:
            • Instance-level firewall  
            • Stateful  
            • Only ALLOW rules  
            • Automatically allows return traffic  
            • Easier and more common  

        NACL:
            • Subnet-level firewall  
            • Stateless  
            • ALLOW + DENY rules  
            • Must allow inbound AND outbound manually  
            • Used for an extra security layer  


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHEN TO USE WHAT?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Security Groups when:
            • Protecting specific EC2/RDS servers  
            • Allowing ports like 22, 80, 443  
            • You want simpler, safer control  

        Use NACL when:
            • You need subnet-wide rules  
            • You want to block specific IPs  
            • Need an additional security layer  


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        NACL = Subnet-level firewall (stateless)  
        SG   = Instance-level firewall (stateful)  

        Together they provide layered network security in AWS.


****************************************************************************************************

EIP:

    WHAT IS AN ELASTIC IP (EIP)?

    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE DEFINITION
    --------------------------------------------------

        An Elastic IP (EIP) in Amazon Web Services (AWS)
        is a static, permanent public IP address that
        belongs to your AWS account — NOT to a specific EC2 instance.

        You can detach it from one EC2 and attach it to another.


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW IS ELASTIC IP DIFFERENT FROM PUBLIC IP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Normal Public IP:
            • Assigned automatically when EC2 starts
            • Changes every time you STOP and START the instance
            • You cannot move it to another EC2
            • Controlled by AWS, not by you

        Elastic IP:
            • Does NOT change after stop/start
            • You can reassign it to any EC2 instantly
            • You own it inside your AWS account
            • Perfect for stable applications


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW IS ELASTIC IP DIFFERENT FROM PRIVATE IP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Private IP:
            • Only for internal VPC communication
            • Not accessible from the internet
            • Every EC2 must have at least one private IP

        Elastic IP:
            • Public internet-accessible IP
            • Used to reach your server from outside AWS


    --------------------------------------------------
    IF WE ALREADY HAVE A PUBLIC IP, WHY DO WE NEED ELASTIC IP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Because:
            Normal public IP changes when you stop/start EC2.

        Many real-world systems NEED a permanent, never-changing IP:
            • Hosting a website
            • SSH access
            • VPN servers
            • Payment systems
            • Third-party integrations
            • DNS records
            • Whitelisting in companies or firewalls

        If the IP changes, everything breaks.

        Elastic IP solves this problem:
            → The IP stays the same forever.


    --------------------------------------------------
    MAIN ADVANTAGES OF ELASTIC IP
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Static public IP (never changes)
        • You control it, not AWS
        • Can move between EC2 instances
        • Useful for failover:
              If one server fails → attach EIP to a new server


    --------------------------------------------------
    LOGIC BEHIND ELASTIC IP (WHY AWS CREATED IT)
    --------------------------------------------------

        • To give customers a stable public IP address  
        • To avoid IP changes after instance restart  
        • To quickly switch traffic to a new EC2 during failures  
        • To support DNS, firewalls, and external integrations  


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Private IP  → Internal AWS communication  
        Public IP   → Internet access, but changes on restart  
        Elastic IP  → Permanent public IP you own and can reassign  

        Elastic IP exists so your public IP never changes.



