ENI:

    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE DEFINITION
    --------------------------------------------------

        In Amazon Web Services (AWS), an NIC is called an
        ENI (Elastic Network Interface).

        Some EC2 instances attach more than one ENI
        when they need to connect to multiple networks
        or require advanced networking.


    --------------------------------------------------
    MAIN REASONS FOR MULTIPLE NICs
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Connecting to Multiple Subnets
           • One ENI in a public subnet (internet-facing)
           • Another ENI in a private subnet (internal traffic)

        2) Security Separation
           • Frontend traffic and backend traffic kept separate
           • Each ENI can have different Security Groups

        3) Firewall / Proxy / NAT Instances
           • These appliances need:
                 - One ENI for incoming traffic
                 - One ENI for outgoing traffic

        4) High Availability / Failover Design
           • ENIs can move between instances
           • Helps in quick recovery if a server fails

        5) Advanced Routing Needs
           • Some architectures require custom routing paths
           • Multi-homed EC2 instances support this

        6) Monitoring or Logging Networks
           • One ENI handles normal traffic
           • Another ENI dedicated for logs or monitoring tools


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        EC2 instances use multiple NICs when they must:
            • Connect to more than one network
            • Separate traffic for security
            • Act as firewalls/proxies/NAT devices
            • Support failover or advanced routing

        Multiple ENIs = better security, isolation, routing, and reliability.



